#Text=Chapter 19
#Text=“ Madame Haupt Hebamme ” , ran a sign , swinging from a second-story window over a saloon on the avenue ; at a side door was another sign , with a hand pointing up a dingy flight of stairs .
#Text=Jurgis went up them , three at a time .
#Text=Madame Haupt was frying pork and onions , and had her door half open to let out the smoke .
#Text=When he tried to knock upon it , it swung open the rest of the way , and he had a glimpse of her , with a black bottle turned up to her lips .
#Text=Then he knocked louder , and she started and put it away .
#Text=She was a Dutchwoman , enormously fat -- when she walked she rolled like a small boat on the ocean , and the dishes in the cupboard jostled each other .
#Text=She wore a filthy blue wrapper , and her teeth were black .
#Text=“ Vot is it ? ” she said , when she saw Jurgis .
#Text=He had run like mad all the way and was so out of breath he could hardly speak .
#Text=His hair was flying and his eyes wild -- he looked like a man that had risen from the tomb . “ My wife ! ” he panted .
#Text=“ Come quickly ! ”
#Text=Madame Haupt set the frying pan to one side and wiped her hands on her wrapper .
#Text=“ You vant me to come for a case ? ” she inquired .
#Text=“ Yes , ” gasped Jurgis .
#Text=“ I haf yust come back from a case , ” she said .
#Text=“ I haf had no time to eat my dinner .
#Text=Still -- if it is so bad -- ”
#Text=“ Yes -- it is ! ” cried he .
#Text=“ Vell , den , perhaps -- vot you pay ? ”
#Text=“ I -- I -- how much do you want ? ” Jurgis stammered .
#Text=“ Tventy-five dollars . ”
#Text=His face fell .
#Text=“ I ca n't pay that , ” he said .
#Text=The woman was watching him narrowly .
#Text=“ How much do you pay ? ” she demanded .
#Text=“ Must I pay now -- right away ? ”
#Text=“ Yes ; all my customers do . ”
#Text=“ I -- I have n't much money , ”
#Text=Jurgis began in an agony of dread .
#Text=“ I 've been in -- in trouble -- and my money is gone .
#Text=But I 'll pay you -- every cent -- just as soon as I can ; I can work -- ”
#Text=“ Vot is your work ? ”
#Text=“ I have no place now .
#Text=I must get one . But I -- ”
#Text=“ How much haf you got now ? ”
#Text=He could hardly bring himself to reply .
#Text=When he said “ A dollar and a quarter , ” the woman laughed in his face .
#Text=“ I vould not put on my hat for a dollar and a quarter , ” she said .
#Text=“ It 's all I 've got , ” he pleaded , his voice breaking .
#Text=“ I must get some one -- my wife will die .
#Text=I ca n't help it -- I -- ”
#Text=Madame Haupt had put back her pork and onions on the stove .
#Text=She turned to him and answered , out of the steam and noise : “ Git me ten dollars cash , und so you can pay me the rest next mont ' . ”
#Text=“ I ca n't do it -- I have n't got it ! ” Jurgis protested .
#Text=“ I tell you I have only a dollar and a quarter . ”
#Text=The woman turned to her work .
#Text=“ I do n't believe you , ” she said .
#Text=“ Dot is all to try to sheat me .
#Text=Vot is de reason a big man like you has got only a dollar und a quarter ? ”
#Text=“ I 've just been in jail , ” Jurgis cried -- he was ready to get down upon his knees to the woman -- “and I had no money before , and my family has almost starved . ”
#Text=“ Vere is your friends , dot ought to help you ? ”
#Text=“ They are all poor , ” he answered .
#Text=“ They gave me this .
#Text=I have done everything I can -- ”
#Text=“ Have n't you got notting you can sell ? ”
#Text=“ I have nothing , I tell you -- I have nothing , ” he cried , frantically .
#Text=“ Ca n't you borrow it , den ?
#Text=Do n't your store people trust you ? ”
#Text=Then , as he shook his head , she went on :
#Text=“ Listen to me -- if you git me you vill be glad of it .
#Text=I vill save your wife und baby for you , and it vill not seem like mooch to you in de end .
#Text=If you loose dem now how you tink you feel den ?
#Text=Und here is a lady dot knows her business -- I could send you to people in dis block , und dey vould tell you -- ”
#Text=Madame Haupt was pointing her cooking-fork at Jurgis persuasively ; but her words were more than he could bear .
#Text=He flung up his hands with a gesture of despair and turned and started away .
#Text=“ It 's no use , ” he exclaimed -- but suddenly he heard the woman 's voice behind him again --
#Text=“ I vill make it five dollars for you . ”
#Text=She followed behind him , arguing with him . “ You vill be foolish not to take such an offer , ” she said .
#Text=“ You vo n't find nobody go out on a rainy day like dis for less .
#Text=Vy , I haf never took a case in my life so sheap as dot .
#Text=I could n't pay mine room rent -- ”
#Text=Jurgis interrupted her with an oath of rage . “ If I have n't got it , ” he shouted , “ how can I pay it ?
#Text=Damn it , I would pay you if I could , but I tell you I have n't got it .
#Text=I have n't got it !
#Text=Do you hear me I have n't got it ! ”
#Text=He turned and started away again .
#Text=He was halfway down the stairs before Madame Haupt could shout to him : “ Vait ! I vill go mit you ! Come back ! ”
#Text=He went back into the room again .
#Text=“ It is not goot to tink of anybody suffering , ” she said , in a melancholy voice .
#Text=“ I might as vell go mit you for noffing as vot you offer me , but I vill try to help you .
#Text=How far is it ? ”
